# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: java-awt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] The **Abstract Window Toolkit** (**AWT**) is Java's original platform-dependent windowing, graphics, and user-interface widget toolkit, preceding Swing.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] The AWT is part of the Java Foundation Classes (JFC) — the standard API for providing a graphical user interface (GUI) for a Java program.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] AWT is also the GUI toolkit for a number of Java ME profiles.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] For example, Connected Device Configuration profiles require Java runtimes on mobile telephones to support the Abstract Window Toolkit.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] When Sun Microsystems first released Java in 1995, AWT widgets provided a thin level of abstraction over the underlying native user-interface.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] For example, creating an AWT check box would cause AWT directly to call the underlying native subroutine that created a check box.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] However, the check box on Windows is not the same as the check box on macOS or on the various types of Unix.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Some application developers prefer this model because it provides a high degree of fidelity to the underlying native windowing toolkit and seamless integration with native applications.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] In other words, a GUI program written using AWT looks like a native Microsoft Windows application when run on Windows, but the same program looks like a native Apple Macintosh application when run on a Mac, etc.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] However, some application developers dislike this model because they prefer their applications to look exactly the same on every platform.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] In J2SE 1.2, the Swing toolkit largely superseded the AWT's widgets.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] In addition to providing a richer set of UI widgets, Swing draws its own widgets (by using Java 2D to call into low-level subroutines in the local graphics subsystem) instead of relying on the operating system's high-level user interface module.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Swing provides the option of using either the native platform's "look and feel" or a cross-platform look and feel (the "Java Look and Feel") that looks the same on all windowing systems.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Neither AWT nor Swing is inherently thread safe.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Therefore, code that updates the GUI or processes events should execute on the Event dispatching thread.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Failure to do so may result in a deadlock or race condition.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] To address this problem, a utility class called SwingWorker allows applications to perform time-consuming tasks following user-interaction events in the event dispatching thread.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Where there is a Swing version of an AWT component it will begin with J- and should be used exclusively, replacing the AWT version.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] For example, in Swing, only use JButton, never Button class.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] As mentioned above, the AWT core classes, such as Color and Font, are still used as-is in Swing.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] When drawing in Swing, use JPanel and override paintComponent(Graphics g) instead of using the AWT paint() methods.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Before Java 6 Update 12, mixing Swing components and basic AWT widgets often resulted in undesired side effects, with AWT widgets appearing on top of the Swing widgets regardless of their defined z-order.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] This problem was because the rendering architecture of the two widget toolkits was very different, despite Swing borrowing heavyweight top containers from AWT.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] Starting in Java 6 Update 12, it is possible to mix Swing and AWT widgets without having z-order problems.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] As the AWT is a bridge to the underlying native user-interface, its implementation on a new operating system may involve a lot of work, especially if it involves any of the AWT GUI widgets, because each of them requires that its native peers be developed from scratch.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] A new project, Caciocavallo, has been created, that provides an OpenJDK-based Java API to ease AWT implementation on new systems.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] The project has successfully implemented AWT widgets using Java2D.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] All the necessary core-JDK modifications have since been pushed to OpenJDK 7, which means that Java can now be used on a graphics stack other than one of those provided by the official JDK (X Window System, OpenGL or DirectX), by including an external library and setting some system properties.
[src:java-awt/abstract-window-toolkit] A DirectFB backend for Caciocavallo is under development, as is an HTML5 backend; the aim is to deploy existing Swing applications—without Java support—as ordinary web applications running on a web server.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:java-awt/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:java-awt/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:java-awt/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:java-awt/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] A **foreign function interface** (**FFI**) is a mechanism by which a program written in one programming language can call interoperable routines or make use of services written or compiled in another one.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] An FFI is often used in contexts where calls are made into a binary dynamic-link library.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] The term comes from the specification for Common Lisp, which explicitly refers to the programming language feature enabling for inter-language calls as such; the term is also often used officially by the interpreter and compiler documentation for Haskell, Rust, PHP, Python, and LuaJIT (Lua).
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Other languages use other terminology: Ada has *language bindings*, while Java has *Java Native Interface* (JNI), *Java Native Access* (JNA), or since Java 22, Foreign Function and Memory API.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Foreign function interface has become generic terminology for mechanisms which provide such services.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] The primary function of a foreign function interface is to mate the semantics and calling conventions of one programming language (the *host* language, or the language which defines the FFI), with the semantics and conventions of another (the *guest* language).
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] This process must also take into consideration the runtime environments and application binary interfaces of both.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] C++ offers compatibility with C trivially, however as C++ uses name mangling, symbols that are to be exported in shared libraries must be wrapped in extern "C" blocks which prevent name mangling.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] `extern "C"` functions may call C++ code internally, but may only return C types and may not throw exceptions.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs can be generated automatically: for example, SWIG.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] However, in the case of an extension language a semantic inversion of the relationship of guest and host can occur, when a smaller body of extension language is the guest invoking services in the larger body of host language, such as writing a small plugin for GIMP.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Some FFIs are restricted to free standing functions, while others also allow calls of functions embedded in an object or class (often called method calls); some even permit migration of complex datatypes or objects across the language boundary.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] In most cases, an FFI is defined by a higher-level language, so that it may employ services defined and implemented in a lower-level language, typically a system programming language like C or C++.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] This is typically done to either access operating system (OS) services in the language in which the OS API is defined, or for performance goals.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Many FFIs also provide the means for the called language to invoke services in the host language also.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] The term foreign function interface is generally not used to describe multi-lingual runtimes such as the Microsoft Common Language Runtime, where a common *substrate* is provided which enables any CLR-compliant language to use services defined in any other.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] There are some special cases, in which the languages compile into the same bytecode VM, like Clojure and Java, as well as Elixir and Erlang.
[src:java-awt/foreign-function-interface] Since there is no interface, it is not an FFI, strictly speaking, while it offers the same functions to the user.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:java-awt/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:java-awt/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] In computing, a **windowing system** (or **window system**) is a software suite that manages separately different parts of display screens.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It is a type of graphical user interface (GUI) which implements the WIMP (windows, icons, menus, pointer) paradigm for a user interface.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Each currently running application is assigned a usually resizable and usually rectangular surface of the display to present its GUI to the user; these windows may overlap each other, as opposed to a tiling interface where they are not allowed to overlap.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Usually a window decoration is drawn around each window.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The programming of both the window decoration and of available widgets inside of the window, which are graphical elements for direct user interaction, such as sliders, buttons, etc., is eased and simplified through the use of widget toolkits.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The main component of any windowing system is usually called the *display server*, although alternative terms such as *window server* are also in use.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Any application that runs and presents its GUI in a window, is a client of the display server.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The display server and its clients communicate with each other over an application programming interface (API) or a communications protocol, which is usually called display server protocol, the display server being the mediator between the clients and the user.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It receives all the input from the kernel, that the kernel receives from all attached input devices, such as keyboard, pointing devices, or touchscreen and transmits it to the correct client.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The display server is also responsible for the output of the clients to the computer monitor.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The output of sound is usually not managed by the display server, but the sound volume is usually handled through GUI applets and it is the display server who decides which applications are on top.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] A windowing system enables the computer user to work with several programs at the same time.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Each program presents its GUI in its own window, which is generally a rectangular area of the screen.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] From a programmer's point of view, a windowing system implements graphical primitives.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] For example: rendering fonts or drawing a line on the screen.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It provides an abstraction of the graphics hardware for use by higher-level elements of the graphical interface such as a window manager.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] A display server protocol can be network capable or even network transparent, facilitating the implementation of thin clients.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] A **display server** or **window server** is a program whose primary task is to coordinate the input and output of its clients to and from the rest of the operating system, the hardware, and each other.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The display server communicates with its clients over the display server protocol, a communications protocol, which can be network-transparent or simply network-capable.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The display server is a key component in any graphical user interface, specifically the windowing system.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The server/client relationship of a standalone display server is somewhat counterintuitive in that a "server" is usually thought of as a large, remote machine, whereas a standalone "display server" is a small local system, with most clients being executed on a larger central machine.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The explanation is that a display server provides the *services* of a display and input devices.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The X Window System was first released in 1984 and is historically the main windowing system for Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The core protocol has been at version 11 since 1987, hence it commonly being known as "X11".
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The current reference implementation of the X11 protocol is the X.Org Server, which provides the display server and some ancillary components.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The X Window System does not define a look and feel; instead, users run a window manager (either standalone or part of a broader desktop environment) and applications designed using a widget toolkit.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The X.Org repository includes a reference window manager, twm; a reference implementation of a widget toolkit, X Athena Widgets; and some basic applications, such as a calculator and clock.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Other notable examples of display servers implementing the X11 display server protocol are XFree86 (from which the current X.Org Server was forked), XQuartz (for macOS) and Cygwin/X (for Microsoft Windows).
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Display servers that implement the Wayland protocol are called Wayland compositors, communicating with clients over the Wayland protocol.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Wayland was created as the intended successor to X11, and differs from X11's design significantly.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] A Wayland compositor combines the functions of a display server, window manager, and compositing manager into one component, whereas in X11 they are separate pieces of software.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The scope of the Wayland protocol is far smaller than X11's core protocol, defining only how clients write data into buffers called "surfaces", and it does not function as a network protocol.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Wayland has seen adoption by several open source desktop environments, including GNOME and KDE Plasma which are porting from X11, and environments like COSMIC which were written from scratch as Wayland-native environments.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Several standalone compositors such as Weston, Sway, Hyprland, Wayfire, niri, labwc are also available.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Wayland has also seen adoption by several embedded and mobile-focused systems, including Tizen, Sailfish OS, and WebOS.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The reference implementation of Wayland is available under the MIT License, consisting of the libwayland-client and libwayland-server libraries.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] There is an ongoing effort to add Wayland support to ChromeOS.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The Mir display server comes with its own Mir display server protocol which is different from those used by X11 and Wayland.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Mir additionally supports the X11 protocol.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It was developed by Canonical and was intended to be the display server of choice for Ubuntu.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] As of 2017, it has been replaced with the Wayland display server for desktop editions of Ubuntu.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] There are implementations of the Mir display server, the libmir-server and the libmir-client libraries available under the GPLv3.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Everything in Android is rendered to a "surface"; "surfaces" are produced by applications and placed into a queue that is managed by SurfaceFlinger.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Yet another Android-specific solution is "Gralloc".
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Gralloc handles device memory i.e. it does allocation, arbitration, it handles synchronization via Android/Linux fence file descriptors.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Gralloc competes with other solutions like e.g.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Mesa's Generic Buffer Management (GBM) or Nvidia's EGLStreams.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] The Gralloc hardware abstraction layer (HAL) is used to allocate the buffers that underlie "surfaces".
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] For compositing in Android, Surfaces are sent to SurfaceFlinger, which uses OpenGL ES to do the compositing.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Hardware Composer HAL (HWC) was introduced in Android 3.0 and has evolved steadily over the years.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Its primary purpose is to determine the most efficient way to composite buffers with the available hardware.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] As a HAL, its implementation is device-specific and usually done by the display hardware OEM.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] For Apple's macOS family of operating systems, Quartz Compositor fulfils the tasks of a display server and of a window manager in the windowing system.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] For Microsoft Windows, from Windows Vista onward, Desktop Window Manager enables the use of hardware acceleration to render the graphical user interface.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It was originally created to enable portions of the new "Windows Aero" user experience, which allowed for effects such as transparency, 3D window switching and more.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] It is also included with Windows Server 2008, but requires the "Desktop Experience" feature and compatible graphics drivers to be installed.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] From Windows 8 onwards DWM can't be disabled and is software rendered if no suitable graphics card is installed.
[src:java-awt/windowing-system] Some systems such as Microsoft Windows (XP, 9x and earlier), the classic Mac OS (version 9 and earlier), and Palm OS, contain a windowing system which is integrated with the OS.
